@rwgk I don't understand your patch yet:
The comment says, GNU's `libstdc++` is good - all other implementations need the self-made hash.

Your patch says LLVM's `libc++` is not good - all other implementations can use the standard hashes.

@dboitnot, sure, that _works_. But If you wanted to split a simple string, you'd just go like this:

```yaml
notifications: {{ "note1; note2; note3".split(";") }}
```

I fear that if we show people examples of using these resolvers in cases where you don't actually _need_ to use them (and where you really _shouldn't_ use them), it will be more confusing. The only times you need to use these resolvers is when you need to combine/manipulate the outputs of other resolvers. I actually added documentation to that effect to make it absolutely clear.

If we fail to read the `fragmentHeader` from `aMessage` then may be better not to ignore it since we then follow with checking `fragmentHeader.GetNextHeader()` (which can be some random value since `fragmentHeader` can remain unassigned).

I suggest we check the next header under an `if` block like: 
```
if (aMessage.Read(aMessage.GetOffset(), fragmentHeader) == kErrorNone) 
{
     // Check if next header is ICMP6 and msg is echo request
```

